A '''''pronunciamiento''''' (literally, “pronouncement” or “declaration”) is the Spanish term for a military uprising or [[coup]] in the history of [[Spain]] and the Spanish American republics. They received this designation because coups were usually accompanied by a statement declaring the existing government null and void. 

In [[Mexico]], where such declarations were often quite detailed, formal, and issued as written texts, they were given the name of '''[[Plans in Mexican History|plans]]'''. In Spain, "pronunciamiento" occured in the 1898 during the reign of Isabel II. General Prim and General Serrano united the force in the revolution in September to drive the queen out of Spain.

